147. We are to observe, that when [p:DIONYSIUS HALYCARNASSAEUS] says, that if we regard the antient walls of [l:*Rome*], the extent of the city will not appear greater than that of [l:*Athens*]; he must mean the ACROPOLIS and high town only. No antient author ever speaks of the PYRAEUM, PHALERUS, and MUNYCHIA, as the same with [l:*Athens*]. Much less can it be supposed, that [p:DIONYSIUS] would consider the matter in that light, after the walls of [p:CIMON] and [p:*Pericles*] were destroyed, and [l:*Athens*] was entirely separated from these other towns. This observation destroys all [p:VOSSIUS]'s reasonings, and introduces common sense into these calculations.

