168. DEMOST. _contra_ LEPT. The *Athenians* brought yearly from [l:PONTUS] 400,000 medimni or bushels of corn, as appeared from the custom-house books. And this was the greatest part of their importation. This by the by is a strong proof that there is some great mistake in the foregoing passage of [p:ATHENAEUS]. For [l:ATTICA] itself was so barren in corn, that it produced not enough even to maintain the peasants. TIT. LIV. lib. 43. cap. 6. [p:*Lucian*], in his _navigium sive vota_, says, that a ship, which by the dimensions he gives, seems to have been about the size of our third rates, carried as much corn as would maintain all [l:ATTICA] for a twelvemonth. But perhaps [l:*Athens*] was decayed at that time; and besides, it is not safe to trust such loose rhetorical calculations.

