{#n203a}
205. [p:QUINTUS CURTIUS] says, its walls were only ten miles in circumference, when founded by [p:*Alexander*]; lib. 4. cap. 8. [p:STRABO], who had travelled to [l:ALEXANDRIA], as well as [p:DIODORUS SICULUS], says it was scarce four miles long, and in most places about a mile broad; lib. 17. [p:*Pliny*] says it resembled a *Macedonian* cassock, stretching out in the corners; lib. 5. cap. 10. Notwithstanding this bulk of [l:ALEXANDRIA], which seems but moderate, [p:DIODORUS SICULUS], speaking of its circuit as drawn by [p:*Alexander*], (which it never exceeded, as we learn from AMMIANUS MARCELLINUS, lib. 22. cap. 16.) says it was $grc:μεγέθει διαφέροντα$, _extremely great_, ibid. The reason why he assigns for its surpassing all cities of the world (for he excepts not [l:*Rome*]) is, that it contained 300,000 free inhabitants. He also mentions the revenues of the kings, _viz_. 6000 talents, as another circumstance to the same purpose: No such mighty sum in our eyes, even though we make allowances for the different value of money. What [p:STRABO] says of the neighbouring country, means only that it was well peopled, $grc:οἰκούμενα καλῶς$. Might not one affirm, without any great hyperbole, that the whole banks of the river from GRAVESEND to [l:WINDSOR] are one city? This is even more than [p:STRABO] says of the banks of the lake MAREOTIS, and of the canal to CANOPUS. 'Tis a vulgar saying in [l:*Italy*], that the King of [l:SARDINIA] has but one town in [l:PIEDMONT]; for it is all a town. [p:AGRIPPA] in JOSEPHUS _de bello_ JUDAIC. lib. 2. cap. 16. to make his audience comprehend the excessive greatness of [l:ALEXANDRIA], which he endeavours to magnify, describes only the compass of the city as drawn by [p:*Alexander*]: A clear proof that the bulk of the inhabitants were lodged there, and that the neighbouring country was no more than what might be expected about all great towns, very well cultivated, and well peopled.

