258. Lib. 2. cap. 62. It may perhaps be imagined, that [p:*Polybius*], being dependent on [l:*Rome*], would naturally extol the *Roman* dominion. But, in the _first_ place, [p:*Polybius*], tho' one sees sometimes instances of his caution, discovers no symptoms of flattery. _Secondly_, This opinion is only delivered in a single stroke, by the by, while he is intent upon another subject; and 'tis allowed, if there be any suspicion of an author's insincerity, that these oblique propositions discover his real opinion better than his more formal and direct assertions.

